          <text>
            The next morning, the fracture is still visible.

            Holloway conducts the wellness check mechanically. Runner helps with maintenance but is quieter than usual. Remedy offers treatments without the usual commentary. Velvet's observations are brief—literal, stripped of the growing depth I'd been seeing.

            Everyone is just going through motions, performing cooperation without the underlying trust.

            Scout is the only one who seems unaffected—Scout doesn't fully understand what happened, only that everyone is sad and that Florence is gone. Scout keeps bouncing to Florence's usual spot, confused when she's not there.

            After breakfast, I make a decision.

            ¶

            I tell Holloway, "I'm going to check on Florence."

            Holloway asks, "Is that wise?"

            I say, "Probably not, but I'm doing it anyway."

            Holloway doesn't stop me. Scout bounces along—a loyal companion in all situations.

            Florence has taken a chamber in the far wing—smaller than the common areas, more isolated. When I knock—well, tap on the wall; there aren't really doors—she sounds surprised.

            Florence says, "Kira?"

            I ask, "Can I come in?"

            A pause.

            Florence says, "Yes."

            The chamber is sparse. Florence's wheeled platform is parked near the wall; a few supplies lie scattered around. Nothing looks like home. She looks smaller here—diminished.

            I sit against the wall. Scout settles beside me, watching Florence curiously.

            I say, "Your advice was good."

            Florence responds, "So I keep hearing—right before someone reminds me that doesn't matter because I lied."

            I ask, "Does it matter to you—that the advice was good?"

            Florence is quiet for a moment, then says, "Yes—and also no. I wanted to help—genuinely wanted to help—and I did help. The solutions I provided worked—but…"

            I finish gently, "But you wanted credit."

            Florence says, "Not credit—recognition. I wanted people to value my thinking, not just tolerate my presence because I carried an elder." Her platform shifts restlessly. "And now I have neither—no elder to carry, no trust to build on—just… Florence, who nobody needs."

            "That's not true," I say.

            Florence asks, "Isn't it? What do I contribute, Kira? I can't move fast, can't access most spaces, need help for basic tasks. My one value was tactical thinking, and I've proven that can't be trusted."

            I counter, "The thinking *CAN* be trusted. You were right about de-escalation—about clear boundaries. That advice is sound."

            Florence makes a small, brittle laugh. "*They're being hurt.* There's a difference."

            I admit, "Yeah. There is."

            Florence says quietly, "I wish I hadn't lied… but I also—I don't know how else it would have worked. They didn't value my judgment before; they do value elders' wisdom. So I gave them what they'd accept—and now I'm being punished for succeeding at helping through the only channel available."
          </text>
