        <chunk>
          <text>
            Holloway says — "ESPECIALLY if the content was helpful. Because it worked! We listened, we trusted, we acted on Florence's guidance thinking it came from ancient wisdom. And it was just… her. Using our respect for elders to bypass our judgment of her."

            I argue — "Your judgment of her was *WRONG*. You didn't value Florence's thinking, so she gave you a package you would value — she was right — you wouldn't have listened otherwise."

            Runner says — "We don't know that."

            I look around at all of them — "Don't we?"

            I continue — "Honestly — if Florence had suggested those same strategies as *HER* ideas, without Elder Twist's authority, would you have taken them as seriously?"

            ¶

            I press — "See? She was right. Her judgment wasn't valued. So she borrowed value from someone you did respect. And it *WORKED*. And now you're punishing her for successfully helping you in the only way available."

            Velvet says simply — "She lied."

            I counter — "She survived. In a system that didn't value her contributions, she found a way to contribute anyway. Maybe that's not ideal, but it's also not villainy."

            Holloway says firmly — "Kira, we understand you're trying to help. But you're not a plant. You don't have the same relationship with authority structures that we do. For us, trust in wisdom requires honesty about source. Florence violated that."

            I remind them — "Your authority structures failed. HR manuals didn't work. Elder Heartwood was irrelevant. You just spent a week learning that external wisdom doesn't actually solve problems better than your own judgment. And now you're angry because Florence proved that point too well?"

            Nobody has an answer to that.

            Before anyone can formulate one, Scout bounces in from patrol — fast, urgent, a bad-news bounce.

            Holloway asks immediately — "What?"

            Scout bounces toward the eastern boundary — more markers, lots more markers.

            We go check.

            The boundary trees are covered in aggressive territorial markings — not a few, but dozens; deeper, fresher, more threatening.

            Runner, tracing the patterns, says — "They're escalating. This isn't warning anymore — this is claiming."

            Holloway asks — "How many plants?"

            Scout bounces — many, organized, coordinated.

            Remedy says — "We need a response. And we need it soon."

            Everyone looks at each other. The weight of Florence's absence is suddenly very present — Florence who had tactical thinking, Florence who suggested de-escalation, Florence who nobody trusts anymore.

            Holloway asks, emphasizing the 'we' — "What do *WE* think? Not what Florence thinks. Not what elders think. What do *WE* think is the right approach?"

            It's a good question. And nobody has a good answer.

            Runner finally says — "Clear boundaries make sense. Whether Florence suggested it or not — showing we're not expanding, that helps."

            Remedy adds — "Delegation could work. Explain our situation, invite dialogue."

            I point out — "So… basically what Florence advised."
          </text>
