          <text>
            Holloway corrects — "Based on sound conflict resolution principles, which Florence recognized—the strategy isn't wrong just because she suggested it first."

            That's technically accepting Florence's advice while refusing to credit her for it—the irony is pretty thick.

            Holloway decides — "We should send the delegation tomorrow. Runner and Velvet—you can approach peacefully, speak for the group."

            Runner asks — "Without Kira?"

            Holloway says — "The hostile plants might react badly to seeing Kira. Better if she stays here where it's safer."

            I don't love that, but I understand the logic.

            Velvet wants to know — "What if they ask about Florence?"

            Holloway asks — "What *ABOUT* Florence?"

            Velvet clarifies — "About whether she's still… with us—part of our group, influencing our decisions."

            Good question. What _IS_ Florence's status now?

            Holloway, careful — "Florence is… taking space—processing her mistakes—not currently participating in group decisions."

            That's technically true and also completely sidesteps the complexity.

            We head back to the facility. Plans are made—Runner and Velvet will approach the hostile plants tomorrow at dawn, deliver a message of peaceful coexistence, invite dialogue.

            It's Florence's strategy—we're just not calling it that.

            ¶

            That night I can't sleep—I keep thinking about Florence alone in that chamber, about trust broken, and whether good advice from a bad source still counts—about how we're fractured at exactly the wrong time.

            The hostile plants are organized, coordinated, escalating.

            And we're weaker than we were yesterday—not because we lost capability—Florence's thinking is still available if we'd use it—but because we lost trust.

            Trust is harder to build than to break.

            I don't know how to build it back—or if there's time to try before the hostile plants make their move.
          </text>
